                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/860</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British, Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">PRO MEMORIA</p>
                <p>In the Sam Francisco Bulletin of October 5 a report is printed as to statements
                    made by G. D. Smith, wireless operator on board the Mexican steamer <hi
                        rend="italic">Mazatlan</hi>, originally under the German flag, before Rear
                    Admiral Pond and other Government authorities on the 4th October at San
                    Francisco, complaining as to violations of neutrality by Captain Fred Jebsen,
                    head of the Jebsen Steamship Company, and Captain zur Helle of San
                    Francisco.</p>
                <p>It was alleged that the <hi rend="italic">Mazatlan</hi> was given clearance
                    papers for Guaymas, although only after a bond of $20,000 had been posted and
                    representation had been made that the coal on board the ship was not for
                    delivery aboard the <hi rend="italic">Leipzig</hi>, but that notwithstanding
                    Jebsen and zur Helle went on board the vessel at San Pedro and arranged for the
                    transfer of the coal from the Mazatlan, to the <hi rend="italic"
                    >Leipzig</hi>.</p>
                <p>The British Embassy would be glad to be informed, if there is no objection, as to
                    the results, of the inquiry made by Rear Admiral Pond and as to any action, if
                    any, which may have r been taken by the United States authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,</closer>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-27">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 27, 1914</hi>.</date>
                </dateline>
            </div>
